Now I have all the context I need. Here's how to build your MCP server:

---

## Program.cs — Stdio transport with DI

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient();  // registers IHttpClientFactory + HttpClient

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

## Tool class — wrapping a REST API

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a resource by its unique ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetResource(
        [Description("The unique resource identifier")] string id,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching resource {Id}", id);
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"https://api.example.com/resources/{id}", cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Search resources by keyword query.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchResources(
        [Description("Search keyword")] string query,
        [Description("Max results to return (1-50)")] int limit = 10,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync(
            $"https://api.example.com/resources?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(query)}&limit={limit}",
            cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

## How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK has two injection styles:

**1. Constructor injection (non-static class, shown above)**
The class is instantiated per-call via DI. Services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, or your own interfaces are injected through the primary constructor. Register them normally in `Program.cs` (`AddHttpClient()`, `AddSingleton<T>()`, etc.).

**2. Method parameter injection (static class)**
DI services appear directly as method parameters alongside the tool's schema parameters:

```csharp
[McpServerToolType]
public static class StaticApiTools
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Ping the API health endpoint.")]
    public static async Task<string> PingApi(
        HttpClient httpClient,              // ← injected by DI, hidden from schema
        CancellationToken cancellationToken) // ← also injected
    {
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync("https://api.example.com/health", cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

**Key rules:**
- `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>`, and any DI-registered service are **auto-injected** and **never appear** in the tool's JSON schema
- Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM
- Every tool method and its exposed parameters **must** have `[Description]` — the LLM relies on these to decide when/how to call the tool

To scaffold this project from scratch:

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n MyApiServer
cd MyApiServer
# Then replace the generated files with the code above
dotnet build && dotnet run
```
